hus completed the proof for\nthe conditional distribution’s error bound as follows:\nEz|yLProCo(y,z)−1\nNyX\niLProCo(y,z)\n≤s\n2\nNyw⊤(Σy)wln2\nδ+ln(2/δ)\n3Nylog(1 + e||w||2−by),\nwhere w= (µ+1−µ−1)/τ.\nTo extend this to the generalization bound across all\nclasses, we apply the union bound. Consequently, with aIEEE TRANSACTIONS ON PATTERN ANAL YSIS AND MACHINE INTELLIGENCE 14\nprobability of at least 1−δ, the following inequality is\nsatisfied:\nE(z,y)LProCo(y,z)≤X\ny∈{−1,1}P(y)\nNyX\niLProCo(y,zi)\n+X\ny∈{−1,1}P(y) ln(2 /δ)\n3Nylog(1 + e||w||2−by)\n+X\ny∈{−1,1}P(y)s\n2\nNyw⊤(Σy)wln2\nδ,\nwhere w= (µ+1−µ−1)/τ. ACKNOWLEDGMENTS\nThis work is supported in part by the National Key R &D\nProgram of China under Grant 2021ZD0140407, the Na-\ntional Natural Science Foundation of China under Grants\n62276150, 42327901. We also appreciate the generous dona-\ntion of computing resources by High-Flyer AI. REFERENCES\n[1] A. Krizhevsky, I. Sutskever, and G. E. Hinton, “Imagenet classifica-\ntion with deep convolutional neural networks,” in NeurIPS , 2017.\n1\n[2] K. He, X. Zhang, S. Ren, and J. Sun, “Deep residual learning for\nimage recognition,” in CVPR , 2016. 1, 3, 8, 9\n[3] G. Huang, Z. Liu, L. Van Der Maaten, and K. Q. Weinberger,\n“Densely connected convolutional networks,” in CVPR , 2017. 1, 3\n[4] S. Ren, K. He, R. Girshick, and J. Sun, “Faster R-CNN: Towards\nreal-time object detection with region proposal networks,” in\nNeurIPS , 2015. 1, 11, 12\n[5] H. Zhao, J. Shi, X. Qi, X. Wang, and J. Jia, “Pyramid scene parsing\nnetwork,” in CVPR , 2017. 1\n[6] O. Russakovsky, J. Deng, H. Su, J. Krause, S. Satheesh, S. Ma,\nZ. Huang, A. Karpathy, A. Khosla, M. Bernstein et al. , “Imagenet\nlarge scale visual recognition challenge,” International Journal of\nComputer Vision , 2015. 1\n[7] G. Van Horn, O. Mac Aodha, Y. Song, Y. Cui, C. Sun, A. Shepard,\nH. Adam, P . Perona, and S. Belongie, “The inaturalist species\nclassification and detection dataset,” in CVPR , 2018. 1, 8\n[8] F. Graf, C. Hofer, M. Niethammer, and R. Kwitt, “Dissecting\nsupervised\n\n            **Your Task**\n\n            Use only the Introduction above as your literature context. External paper databases, arXiv, author-profile APIs, and web search are not part of this benchmark.\n\n            1. **Context analysis**: Summarize the problem setting, prior approaches mentioned in the Introduction, and implied gaps you can infer from that text alone.\n\n            2. **Brainstorming**: Collaboratively brainstorm potential research ideas that build upon or address gaps in the Introduction.\n\n            3. **Summarization**: Summarize your collective ideas.\n\n            4. **Formulate a New Research Idea**: Develop a new research proposal in the format of the '5q', defined below:\n\n               **Here is a high-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning.**\n\n               **Here are the five core questions:**\n\n               **[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\n\n               Formulate the specific research question you aim to address. Only output one question and do not include any more information.\n\n               **[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\n\n               Explain the broader implications of solving this problem for the research community.\n               Discuss how such a paper will affect future research.\n               Discuss how addressing this question could advance knowledge or lead to practical applications.\n\n               **[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\n\n               Discuss the challenges and complexities involved in solving this problem.\n               Explain why naive or straightforward approaches may fail.\n               Identify any technical, theoretical, or practical obstacles that need to be overcome. MAKE IT CLEAR.\n\n               **[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\n\n               Identify gaps or limitations in previous research or existing solutions.\n               Discuss any barriers that have prevented this problem from being solved until now.\n               Explain how your approach differs from or improves upon prior work. MAKE IT CLEAR.\n\n               **[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\n\n               Outline your proposed methodology in detail, including the method, dataset, and metrics that you plan to use.\n               Describe the expected outcomes. MAKE IT CLEAR.\n\n            Please work together to produce the '5q' for your proposed research idea.\n\n            Good luck!\n            "}, 'task_results': [{'agent_id': 'agent1', 'result': "Result from the model:### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe introduction discusses the role of learnable parameters in contrastive learning for long-tailed recognition, specifically focusing on the ProCo loss function. The goal is to maintain opacity properties while constructing interconnected symbolic models for networks of discrete-time nonlinear control systems.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- Incorporation of class complement in the construction of positive and negative pairs.\n- Use of simulation functions to maintain opacity properties.\n- Analysis of the ProCo loss function and its asymptotic expansion.\n- Examination of the 1-Lipschitz property of the function.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- The introduction mentions the need for maintaining opacity properties while enabling the construction of interconnected symbolic models, which suggests a gap in the current methods for ensuring both opacity and model interconnectedness.\n- There is a need for a more robust theoretical foundation and practical application of the ProCo loss function, especially in the context of long-tailed recognition.\n- The introduction does not explicitly address the scalability and generalizability of the proposed methods to different types of datasets and control systems.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Enhancing Opacity in Interconnected Models:**\n   - Develop a framework that integrates opacity-preserving finite abstractions with decentralized controller synthesis to ensure both safety and security in interconnected cyber-physical systems.\n\n2. **Scalability and Generalizability of ProCo Loss:**\n   - Investigate the scalability of the ProCo loss function to different types of datasets and control systems.\n   - Explore the generalizability of the ProCo loss function across various long-tailed recognition tasks.\n\n3. **Theoretical Foundations and Practical Applications:**\n   - Provide a more rigorous theoretical analysis of the ProCo loss function, including its convergence properties and robustness to noise.\n   - Develop practical applications of the ProCo loss function in real-world scenarios, such as autonomous systems and robotics.\n\n4. **Integration of Explainable AI (XAI):**\n   - Integrate XAI techniques to evaluate the correctness of feature attribution algorithms in the context of contrastive learning.\n   - Develop methods to explain the decisions made by the ProCo loss function, enhancing transparency and trust in the model.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe research should focus on enhancing opacity in interconnected models and improving the scalability and generalizability of the ProCo loss function. A rigorous theoretical analysis and practical applications in real-world scenarios are also essential.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nThe ProCo loss function is a promising approach for contrastive learning in long-tailed recognition, but its scalability, generalizability, and theoretical foundations need further exploration to ensure robustness and practical applicability.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we enhance the scalability and generalizability of the ProCo loss function while maintaining opacity properties in interconnected models?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nSolving this problem will advance the field of contrastive learning by providing a more robust and versatile loss function. It will also enhance the security and reliability of interconnected cyber-physical systems, leading to practical applications in autonomous systems and robotics.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nThe challenge lies in balancing the need for opacity with the scalability and generalizability of the ProCo loss function. Naive approaches may fail to maintain opacity while scaling to different datasets and control systems. Technical and theoretical obstacles include ensuring convergence properties and robustness to noise.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on maintaining opacity properties but has not fully addressed the scalability and generalizability of the ProCo loss function. There is a gap in the theoretical foundations and practical applications of the function.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed methodology includes a rigorous theoretical analysis of the ProCo loss function, focusing on its convergence properties and robustness to noise. We will also develop a framework that integrates opacity-preserving finite abstractions with decentralized controller synthesis. The expected outcomes include a more scalable and generalizable ProCo loss function, validated through experiments on various datasets and control systems.\n"}, {'agent_id': 'agent2', 'result': "Result from the model:### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe introduction discusses the use of learnable parameters in contrastive learning for long-tailed recognition, specifically focusing on the ProCo loss function. The goal is to understand and improve the performance of this loss function in generating positive and negative pairs for training models.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- Recent studies have incorporated class complement in the construction of positive and negative pairs.\n- The ProCo loss function is used to measure the discrepancy between predicted and actual labels, with a focus on its asymptotic expansion and 1-Lipschitz property.\n- The introduction mentions the use of ResNet-50 backbone on LVIS v1 dataset for evaluating the ProCo loss.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- The introduction suggests that while the ProCo loss function has been validated, there is a need for further exploration into its generalization bounds and error bounds across different classes.\n- There is an opportunity to improve the efficiency and effectiveness of the ProCo loss function, particularly in handling long-tailed recognition tasks.\n- The introduction does not mention any specific methods for optimizing the learnable parameters (w) or the bias term (b) in the context of long-tailed recognition.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Optimization of Learnable Parameters:**\n   - Develop a method to dynamically adjust the learnable parameters (w) and bias term (b) to better handle long-tailed recognition tasks.\n   - Explore the impact of different initialization strategies for these parameters on the performance of the ProCo loss.\n\n2. **Generalization Bounds:**\n   - Investigate the generalization bounds of the ProCo loss function across different classes and datasets.\n   - Develop a theoretical framework to analyze the variance and bias trade-off in the ProCo loss.\n\n3. **Error Bounds:**\n   - Derive tighter error bounds for the ProCo loss function to improve its robustness and reliability.\n   - Explore the impact of different sampling strategies on the error bounds of the ProCo loss.\n\n4. **Application to Long-Tailed Recognition:**\n   - Apply the ProCo loss function to long-tailed recognition tasks and evaluate its performance.\n   - Compare the performance of the ProCo loss with other contrastive learning methods in long-tailed recognition tasks.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe key a