to the intended audience. For example, if the intended audience is a research team, the finalized proposal will be submitted to the research team. If the intended audience is a funding agency, the finalized proposal will be submitted to the funding agency. If the intended audience is a journal, the finalized proposal will be submitted to the journal.\n\n### Finalized Research Proposal\n\n#### 1. Literature Review\n\n**Embodied AI and Long-Horizon Planning:**\nEmbodied AI involves AI systems that interact with the physical world through sensors and actuators. Long-horizon planning is essential for these systems to achieve complex tasks over extended periods. Existing approaches often rely on predefined action constraints, limiting their adaptability and versatility. For instance, GPT-4V-based methods can handle a wide range of tasks but are constrained by their predefined action sets, which may not cover all possible scenarios.\n\n**ReLEP Framework:**\nThe ReLEP framework addresses these limitations by using a fine-tuned large vision language model to decompose tasks into skill functions, incorporating a Memory module for plan recall, and a Robot Configuration module for versatility across different robot types. However, there are opportunities to enhance its scalability, robustness, and adaptability.\n\n#### 2. Methodology\n\n**Enhancements to ReLEP:**\n- **Flexible Task Decomposition Strategy:** We will develop a flexible task decomposition strategy using a fine-tuned large vision language model. This model will be trained on a diverse set of tasks and scenarios to improve its ability to generate skill functions tailored to specific instructions and scene images. The use of a large vision language model allows the framework to handle a wider range of tasks and scenarios, overcoming the limitations of predefined action sets.\n- **Diverse Skill Function Library:** The skill function library will be expanded by curating a diverse set of skills from various domains. The criteria for selecting and including new skills will be based on their relevance to the task at hand and their ability to improve the framework's adaptability. This will ensure that the framework can handle a wide range of tasks and scenarios.\n- **Improved Memory Management Module:** The memory management module will be enhanced to improve plan recall and adaptability. This will be achieved by incorporating a memory module that allows for effective plan and status recall, alongside a Robot Configuration module that enhances versatility across different robot types.\n\n#### 3. Experimental Setup\n\n**Datasets:**\n- **Real-World Embodied Tasks:** We will use datasets of real-world embodied tasks to evaluate the framework's performance. These datasets will include a wide range of tasks and scenarios to test the framework's adaptability.\n- **Simulated Environments:** We will use simulated environments to test the framework's adaptability to different scenarios. These environments will be designed to mimic real-world scenarios, allowing us to evaluate the framework's performance in a controlled setting.\n\n**Evaluation Metrics:**\n- **Task Completion Rate:** The percentage of tasks completed successfully will be measured to evaluate the framework's performance.\n- **Plan Efficiency:** The efficiency of the generated plans will be evaluated by measuring the time taken to complete tasks and the number of actions required.\n- **Adaptability:** The framework's ability to adapt to different robot types and scenarios will be assessed by evaluating its performance across a wide range of tasks and scenarios.\n\n#### 4. Expected Results\n\n- **Improved Performance:** The framework will demonstrate improved performance in handling complex long-horizon tasks by generating more efficient and effective plans.\n- **Increased Versatility:** The framework will be more versatile, capable of adapting to different robot types and scenarios by leveraging a diverse skill function library and an improved memory management module.\n- **Better Adaptability:** The framework will be better equipped to handle real-world environments, leading to more robust and intelligent AI systems by incorporating a memory module for plan recall and a Robot Configuration module for versatility across different robot types.\n\n#### 5. Timeline and Milestones\n\n- **Month 1-2: Literature Review and Methodology Development**\n  - Conduct a comprehensive literature review to understand the current state of research in embodied AI and long-horizon planning.\n  - Develop the proposed enhancements to the ReLEP framework, including a flexible task decomposition strategy, a diverse skill function library, and an improved memory management module.\n  \n- **Month 3-4: Dataset Preparation and Initial Testing**\n  - Prepare the datasets for evaluation, including real-world embodied tasks and simulated environments.\n  - Conduct initial testing of the enhanced ReLEP framework to evaluate its performance and identify areas for improvement.\n  \n- **Month 5-6: Framework Evaluation and Optimization**\n  - Evaluate the framework using the prepared datasets, focusing on task completion rate, plan efficiency, and adaptability.\n  - Optimize the framework based on the evaluation results to improve its performance and adaptability.\n  \n- **Month 7-8: Final Testing and Report Preparation**\n  - Conduct final testing of the enhanced ReLEP framework to ensure its performance meets the expected results.\n  - Prepare the final research report, summarizing the methodology, experimental setup, expected results, and timeline for the project.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe proposed research aims to enhance the ReLEP framework for real-world long-horizon embodied planning, making it more scalable, robust, and adaptable. The detailed research proposal outlines the methodology, experimental setup, expected results, and timeline for the project. This proposal will serve as a blueprint for the research and can be shared with the research team or submitted for funding or publication.\n"}, {'agent4': 'Result from the model:To proceed with refining the draft document based on the provided plan and the refined research proposal, I will structure the document according to the outlined sections. Here is the comprehensive draft document:\n\n### Draft Document\n\n#### Introduction\n- **Overview of the Problem:** Contrastive learning is a powerful approach for representation learning, but it faces significant challenges in long-tailed recognition tasks where some classes are underrepresented. Traditional contrastive learning methods often struggle to effectively learn representations for these minority classes, leading to suboptimal performance.\n- **Importance:** Extending the ProCo loss function to federated learning is crucial for addressing these challenges while ensuring data privacy and efficiency. This research will contribute to the development of more robust and secure federated learning systems, with practical applications in sensitive domains such as healthcare and finance.\n- **Objectives:** The primary goals of this research are to integrate the ProCo loss function with the DPBalance mechanism in federated learning, evaluate its performance on long-tailed recognition tasks, and provide insights into the effectiveness of this approach.\n\n#### Literature Review\n- **Contrastive Learning:** Contrastive learning aims to learn representations by maximizing the similarity between positive pairs and minimizing the similarity between negative pairs. The ProCo loss function is a recent advancement that incorporates class complement in the construction of positive and negative pairs, improving the robustness of contrastive learning.\n- **Federated Learning:** Federated learning enables multiple devices or organizations to collaboratively train a model without sharing their data. The DPBalance mechanism is a novel privacy budget scheduling mechanism that optimizes both efficiency and fairness in federated learning.\n- **Long-tailed Recognition:** Long-tailed recognition tasks involve datasets with a highly imbalanced class distribution. Existing solutions often struggle to effectively learn representations for minority classes, leading to suboptimal performance. The integration of the ProCo loss function with federated learning aims to address these challenges.\n\n#### Methodology\n- **Datasets:** The LVIS v1 dataset and other long-tailed recognition datasets will be used for empirical validation. These datasets provide a diverse range of classes and are well-suited for evaluating the performance of the proposed approach.\n- **Metrics:** Performance metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score will be used to evaluate the proposed solution. Additionally, privacy metrics will be considered to ensure that the DPBalance mechanism effectively protects data privacy.\n- **Approach:** The ProCo loss function will be integrated with the DPBalance mechanism to optimize privacy and efficiency in federated learning. The approach will involve developing algorithms and simulation techniques to handle the increased computational load and ensure effective learning in federated settings.\n\n#### Results\n- **Expected Outcomes:** The proposed solution is expected to improve performance metrics in long-tailed recognition tasks while maintaining data privacy. The integration of the ProCo loss function with the DPBalance mechanism is anticipated to lead to more accurate and reliable models in federated learning.\n- **Evaluation:** The results will be measured and compared with existing methods using the specified performance and privacy metrics. Extensive experiments and simulations will be conducted to validate the proposed approach.\n\n#### Conclusion\n- **Summary:** The research aims to extend the ProCo loss function to federated learning settings to improve privacy and efficiency in long-tailed recognition tasks. The proposed solution combines the ProCo loss function with the DPBalance mechanism, addressing both privacy and efficiency challenges in federated learning.\n- **Future Work:** Potential areas for future research include exploring the integration of the proposed approach with other federated learning mechanisms, investigating the impact of different data distributions on performance, and developing an explainable AI framework to interpret the decisions made by the ProCo loss function.\n\n#### References\n- **Citations:** Relevant references from the Introduction and Literature Review sections will be included to support the research proposal.\n\n#### Appendices (if necessary)\n- **Proofs and Additional Details:** Any additional mathematical proofs, detailed derivations, or supplementary material will be provided in the appendices.\n\n### Deliverables\n- A comprehensive draft document outlining the methodology, datasets, and expected outcomes.\n- A well-structured and detailed research proposal.\n\n### Next Steps\n- Review the draft with peers or mentors for feedback.\n- Iterate based on feedback to finalize the proposal.\n\nThis draft document provides a detailed and well-organized outline of the research proposal, ensuring that it is comprehensive, clear, and well-structured.\n'}, {'agent5': 'Result from the model:Based on the structured outline and the refined research questions, here is a draft of the research proposal for your work on Task-Oriented Affordances of Objects (TOAO) and the GauTOAO framework:\n\n---\n\n### Draft the Proposal\n\n#### 1. Introduction\n**Background and Motivation:**\nThe field of robotic perception and interaction is crucial for enabling robots to understand and manipulate objects in diverse and complex environments. Task-Oriented Affordances of Objects (TOAO) play a pivotal role in this process by identifying the parts of objects that are relevant for specific tasks. The Gaussian-based framework (GauTOAO) introduces a novel approach to predict affordance-relevant regions of objects in a zero-shot manner, significantly improving robotic performance. However, there is a need for further refinement to enhance the accuracy and robustness of these predictions.\n\n**Problem Statement:**\nThe main problem is the need to refine the Gaussian-based framework (GauTOAO) to improve affordance prediction in zero-shot scenarios. Current methods may not generalize well to new, unseen objects, leading to suboptimal performance in robotic manipulation tasks.\n\n**Research Objectives:**\n- To develop a refined Gaussian-based framework (GauTOAO) that improves the prediction of affordance-relevant regions in zero-shot scenarios.\n- To integrate GauTOAO with the ReLEP framework for improved long-horizon planning in embodied AI.\n- To conduct a comprehensive evaluation of the refined framework using real-world datasets and metrics.\n\n#### 2. Literature Review\n**Related Work:**\nExisting approaches to affordance prediction often rely on static models that may not generalize well to new, unseen objects. GauTOAO addresses this limitation by leveraging vision-language models to predict affordance-relevant regions in a zero-shot manner. However, the framework can be further improved to better handle diverse and complex environments.\n\n**Theoretical Background:**\nThe theoretical foundations of Gaussian-based models and vision-language integration are essential for understanding the impact of GauTOAO on affordance prediction. Gaussian models provide a probabilistic framework for modeling uncertainty, while vision-language models enable the integration of visual and textual information to enhance prediction accuracy.\n\n#### 3. Methodology\n**Theoretical Framework:**\nWe propose a theoretical framework to understand the impact of Gaussian-based predictions on affordance understanding. This framework will analyze the role of vision-language models in enhancing the accuracy of affordance predictions.\n\n**Algorithm Development:**\nWe will develop an algorithm to dynamically adjust parameters based on the distribution of affordance-relevant regions. This algorithm will incorporate a feedback loop to refine predictions based on real-world interactions.\n\n**Datasets:**\nWe will use datasets such as YCB-Video, ObjectNet, and custom datasets for training and evaluation. These datasets provide a diverse range of objects and scenarios to test the robustness of the GauTOAO framework.\n\n**Evaluation Metrics:**\nWe will define evaluation metrics including accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and generalization bounds to assess the performance of the refined framework.\n\n#### 4. Expected Results\n**Performance Improvements:**\nWe expect our refined GauTOAO framework to improve the accuracy and robustness of affordance predictions in zero-shot scenarios, leading to enhanced performance in robotic manipulation tasks. Additionally, we anticipate deeper theoretical insights into Gaussian-based affordance prediction and the role of vision-language models.\n\n**Theoretical Advancements:**\nWe expect to advance the theoretical understanding of Gaussian-based affordance prediction and provide insights into the role of vision-language models in affordance understanding.\n\n#### 5. Challenges and Limitations\n**Challenges:**\nThe main challenges include balancing bias and variance in the Gaussian-based framework and handling the complexity of diverse environments. We will address these challenges through data augmentation and efficient algorithm design.\n\n**Limitations:**\nPotential limitations include dataset bias and computational complexity. We will propose solutions such as data augmentation and efficient algorithm design to mitigate these issues.\n\n#### 6. Conclusion\n**Summary:**\nThis research aims to refine the Gaussian-based framework (GauTOAO) for improved affordance prediction in zero-shot scenarios, enhancing robotic perception and interaction. The integration of GauTOAO with the ReLEP framework will enable improved long-horizon planning in embodied AI.\n\n**Future Work:**\nFuture work will explore extending the framework to other robotic tasks and practical applications. We will also investigate the use of additional datasets and advanced machine learning techniques to further enhance the framework.\n\n**Applications:**\nThe research has practical applications in real-world scenarios, such as autonomous robots in manufacturing, service industries, and healthcare, where accurate and robust affordance prediction is crucial.\n\n---\n\n### Next Steps:\n- Draft the proposal based on the refined questions and methodology.\n- Seek feedback from peers or mentors.\n- Finalize the proposal and prepare for submission or presentation.\n\nThis structured approach will help you refine and finalize your research proposal effectively.\n'}], 'summary': '```json\n{\n  "[Question 1] - What is the problem?": "How can contrastive learning methods be improved to better handle long-tailed recognition tasks, particularly in terms of learning effective representations for underrepresented classes?",\n\n  "[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?": "Addressing this problem is crucial for advancing the robustness and fairness of machine learning models in real-world applications where class imbalance is common. Improved contrastive learning methods can lead to better performance in various domains, such as healthcare, security, and autonomous systems, by ensuring that minority classes are adequately represented and recognized.",\n\n  "[Question 3] - Why is it hard?": "The challenge lies in developing contrastive learning techniques that can effectively capture and utilize information from minority classes without being dominated by majority classes. Naive approaches may fail due to the inherent bias towards more frequent classes, leading to suboptimal representations. Technical obstacles include designing loss functions that are sensitive to class distribution and ensuring computational 